<TITLE> India pile on agony after Sehwag misses triple century </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 MUMBAI, Dec 4 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Virender Sehwag fell seven runs short of a record-breaking third triple century but India continued their domination of the third and final Test against Sri Lanka Friday. Sehwag resumed on his overnight score of 284 but was caught and bowled by master spinner Muttiah Muralitharan for 293, before Sachin Tendulkar struck 48 not out to guide India to 536 for three at lunch on the third day, with Vangipurappu Laxman on 22. Starting the day on 443-1 in reply to Sri Lanka's first-innings 393, India lost Sehwag in the fourth over, much to the disappointment of an expectant and packed Brabourne Stadium Then, left-arm paceman Chanaka Welegedara struck in his first over of the day when he had overnight batsman Rahul Dravid, who scored centuries in the previous two Tests, caught behind for 74 to briefly raise Sri Lankan hopes of a revival. However, Tendulkar shared in a 49-run stand for the unbeaten fourth wicket with Laxman to build on Sehwag's magnificent effort as the hosts took their lead to 143 in pursuit of a victory that would secure India's spot at the top of the Test rankings. Sehwag, only the third batsman to score two triple centuries after Australia's Don Bradman and West Indian Brian Lara, had shared in double century stands with opener Murali Vijay (87) and Dravid on the second day to put India in command. Tillakaratne Dilshan struck a century and Angelo Mathews made 99 in the Sri Lankan innings. India hold a 1-0 after they won the second Test by an innings and 144 runs. The first Test ended in a dr
